{
  "id": "019cdfb4-f69e-7f20-bf73-dd9db3cee3d3",
  "content": "# Content Pipeline Enforcement Architecture (2026-03-12)\n\n## Decision: Two-layer enforcement model\n\n### Layer 1: Deterministic (code guarantees — always reliable)\nAlready built:\n- `tools/carousel-render/render.js` — overflow detection (DOM scrollHeight), font size audit (computed styles), content height budget (pixel math), file existence/size checks\n- Pre-flight checks — HTTP server reachable, Chromium installed\n\nStill to build:\n- **CSS linter** — parse carousel HTML, extract all font-size values, check against `docs/marketing/design-system.json` typography scale. No LLM needed.\n- **Template structure validator** — check slide HTML matches expected template (cover has max 4 title lines, stat-highlight uses grid not flex, etc.). Deterministic.\n- **Package name checker** — grep HTML for npm package names, verify they exist on npm registry. Would have caught the `@anthropic-ai/mcp-server-playwright` error automatically.\n\n### Layer 2: Probabilistic (LLM judgment — best-effort)\n- Content verification via independent agent (`.agents/skills/content-verification.md`)\n- Claim extraction, fact-checking via web search, fairness review\n- Pydantic structured output forces LLM to fill structured form (claim type, verdict, source) so code can inspect results\n- But: LLM can still misjudge. Pydantic guarantees data shape, NOT content truthfulness.\n\n## Framework Evaluation\n\n### LangChain\n- Best value: `langchain-mcp-adapters` (connects to corvia MCP from Python), `CorviaRetriever` (product opportunity for ecosystem visibility)\n- Not needed for: structured output (Anthropic native `messages.parse()` is equivalent), rendering (render.js is purpose-built), workflow gating (Python if/else)\n- Costs: ~40-60 transitive packages, 40% performance overhead in benchmarks, version churn history\n\n### LangGraph\n- Overkill for linear pipeline with one conditional gate\n- Value kicks in at complex branching, parallel agents, human-in-the-loop\n- Even LangChain's own social-media-agent uses LangGraph not LCEL, confirming LCEL chains aren't enough for verified content\n\n### Pydantic + Direct Anthropic SDK (recommended for verification gate)\n- ~100 lines, ~10-15 packages, no framework lock-in\n- `Claim` model with `@field_validator` — stats without sources raise ValidationError\n- `VerificationReport` with typed verdict enum — code gate blocks rendering on NEEDS_REVISION\n- Any AI tool can shell out to `python verify_and_render.py`\n\n### Skills (keep as knowledge layer)\n- `.agents/skills/visual-content-playwright.md` — workflow, pitfalls, design constraints, queryable lessons\n- `.agents/skills/content-verification.md` — verification protocol and fairness standards\n- Portable: any AI tool (Claude Code, Codex, Cursor, Copilot) reads markdown\n- Not enforcing: steps are \"mandatory\" because instructions say so, agent can skip\n\n## Product Opportunity\n- `langchain-corvia` retriever package (~100 lines) → gets corvia on LangChain integrations page\n- MCP server is the real integration surface (already works with all MCP-compatible tools)\n\n## Next Steps (when returning to this)\n1. Build deterministic validators (CSS linter, template checker, package name verifier)\n2. Build Pydantic verification gate script (`tools/carousel-render/verify_and_render.py`)\n3. Consider `langchain-corvia` retriever package for ecosystem visibility",
